        {
          "id": 30992,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">L-type calcium channels are responsible for the rapid depolarization seen in phase 0 of the ventricular myocyte action potential.</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 30993,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">L-type calcium channels facilitate the late influx of potassium ions during phase 2, the plateau phase, of the ventricular action potential.</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 30994,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">L-type calcium channels initiate the action potential in ventricular myocytes by allowing sodium ions to enter rapidly during phase 0.</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 30995,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">L-type calcium channels contribute to the plateau phase by permitting a sustained influx of calcium ions during phase 2 of the ventricular action potential.</span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">During a cardiology fellowship roundtable discussion, a challenging clinical case involving the pharmacological management of a patient with ventricular tachycardia prompts an in-depth analysis of cardiac ion channel physiology. Given the nuances of ion channel function in cardiac myocytes, which of the following statements accurately reflects the characteristics and role of L-type calcium channels in the cardiac action potential?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3169249",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33316,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans.</strong></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\"> </span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>D) L-type calcium channels contribute to the plateau phase by permitting a sustained influx of calcium ions during phase 2 of the ventricular action potential.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D.&nbsp;</strong>L-type calcium channels open during phase 2 of the ventricular action potential, allowing calcium to enter the cell (Influx), (while the K+ efflux simultaneously continues), which prolongs the depolarization phase and contributes to the characteristic plateau phase of the cardiac action potential.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation</u>:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A. Incorrect.&nbsp;</strong>The rapid depolarization seen in phase 0 of the ventricular myocyte action potential is primarily due to the opening of <strong>voltage-gated sodium channels</strong>, not L-type calcium channels.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B. Incorrect.&nbsp;</strong>L-type calcium channels are responsible for <strong>calcium influx</strong>, not potassium influx, and they contribute to phase 2 of the action potential, which maintains the plateau phase, not initiating it.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C. Incorrect.&nbsp;</strong>The initiation of the action potential in <strong>ventricular myocytes</strong> is due to the rapid entry of <strong>sodium ions</strong> through voltage-gated sodium channels, not through L-type calcium channels.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Understand the <strong>function</strong> and importance of <strong>L-type calcium channels</strong> in the <strong>plateau phase</strong> of the <strong>ventricular myocyte</strong> action potential.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Refer</u>: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology, 2<sup>nd</sup> South Asia Edition, Pg No : 182</strong></span></p>",
