      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 30820,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Closure of AV valves</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 30821,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Atrial systole</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 30822,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Closure of semilunar valves</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 30823,
          "text": "<p><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Rapid ejection</span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">A 60-year-old man with a history of hypertension and hypercholesterolemia presents to your office for a routine cardiovascular examination. During auscultation, you note a prominent heart sound immediately following the T-wave on the ECG. Referring to the heart sound indicated by the purple arrow in the provided phonocardiogram, what is the most likely cause of this sound?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The following heart sound marked (purple arrow) in the picture will be heard because of?</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/27/3.jpg\" style=\"height:135px; width:300px\" /></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3675879",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33314,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. C) Closure of semilunar valves&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option C:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Correct</strong>. As indicated by the purple arrow, the <strong>timing</strong> corresponds with the expected <strong>occurrence</strong> of <strong>S2</strong>, which is associated with the <strong>closure</strong> of the <strong>semilunar valves</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>heart sound</strong> marked here is the <strong>second heart sound. </strong>The second heart sound (called S2) will be heard because of the <strong>closure</strong> of the <strong>aortic valve</strong> (left side) and <strong>pulmonary valve</strong> (right side).</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option A:</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. The closure of the <strong>atrioventricular</strong> (AV) valves (tricuspid and mitral valves) occurs at the start of <strong>ventricular systole</strong> and produces the <strong>first heart sound</strong> (S1).</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option B :</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. Atrial systole occurs just before the <strong>first heart sound</strong> and is typically silent, although it may lead to a <strong>fourth heart sound</strong> (S4) in cases of stiff or <strong>hypertrophic</strong> ventricles.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option D :</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Incorrect</strong>. Rapid ejection of blood from the ventricles into the arteries occurs during <strong>mid-systole</strong> and does not produce a <strong>heart sound</strong>; rather, it is part of the events between S1 and S2.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The educational objective of this question is to identify and correlate specific heart sounds with their physiological origins within the cardiac cycle, particularly the <strong>second heart sound</strong> with the <strong>closure</strong> of the <strong>semilunar valves</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\"><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/27/4.jpg\" style=\"height:154px; width:500px\" /></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Mechanisms of different heart sounds:</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/27/screenshot-2024-02-27-160607.jpg\" style=\"height:480px; width:1000px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Refer</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology, 2<sup>nd</sup> South Asia Edition, Pg No : 213</span></strong></span></span></p>",
