      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 30924,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Mild environmental temperature fluctuations &ndash; Cardiac output remains stable </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 30925,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Physical exertion &ndash; Cardiac output escalates </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 30926,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Congestive heart failure on both sides of the heart &ndash; Cardiac output diminishes </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 30927,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Tachyarrhythmias &ndash; Cardiac output surges</span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In a clinical cardiology training session focusing on the physiologic and pathophysiologic determinants of cardiac output, participants are presented with scenarios depicting various conditions and their typical effects on cardiac output. They are tasked with identifying the mismatched pair in terms of the condition&#39;s usual impact on cardiac output:</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2020099",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 33315,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        2
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Ans.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>D) Tachyarrhythmias &ndash; Cardiac output surges</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D. Incorrect.&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Rapid arrhythmias, particularly those that significantly <strong>increase heart rate</strong>, can actually <strong>decrease cardiac output</strong>. This is due to the <strong>shortened diastolic filling time</strong>, which reduces the volume of <strong>blood ejected</strong> with each heartbeat, contrary to the <strong>increase</strong> suggested in this option.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">:</span></strong> </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A. Correct.&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Mild changes in environmental temperature typically do not induce significant <strong>alterations</strong> in <strong>cardiac output</strong>, as the body&#39;s <strong>thermoregulatory mechanisms</strong> effectively maintain cardiovascular homeostasis without necessitating changes in <strong>cardiac output</strong>.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B. Correct.&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">During exercise, the body&#39;s demand for <strong>oxygen</strong> and <strong>nutrients</strong> rises, leading to an <strong>increase</strong> in <strong>cardiac output</strong>. This is achieved through <strong>heightened heart rate</strong> and <strong>stroke volume</strong>, facilitating enhanced blood flow to active muscles.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C. Correct.&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">In cases of <strong>biventricular failure</strong>, both the left and right sides of the heart are unable to pump blood effectively, resulting in <strong>reduced cardiac output</strong>. This condition leads to inadequate perfusion and accumulation of fluid, manifesting as congestive symptoms.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong><u> </u></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Discern the impact of various <strong>physiological</strong> and <strong>pathological</strong> conditions on <strong>cardiac output</strong>, emphasizing the importance of <strong>heart rate</strong> and <strong>ventricular filling</strong> in determining cardiac performance.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Other important factors affecting cardiac output:</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/02/28/9.jpg\" style=\"height:290px; width:500px\" /></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Refer</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: Ganong&rsquo;s Review of Medical Physiology, 25<sup>th</sup> Edition, Pg No: 544</span></strong></span></span></p>",
